ctions, labouring-status wives exercised agency by protecting their marital goods from harm, using legal statutes to their own advantage.In looking at the experiences of labouring-status women, this monograph shifts the debate regarding women’s access to and control of property in the medieval period. Exploring a group previously unexamined by scholars, it argues that our understanding of women’s marital strategies changes, challenging the central role of blood and marital kin in these negotiations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDowryzSpainzValenciaxHistoryy15th century. 0aMarriagezSpainzValenciaxHistoryy15th century. 0aWiveszSpainzValenciaxSocial conditionsy15th century. 0aWomen employeeszSpainzValenciaxSocial conditionsy15th century. 0aWomenzSpainzValenciaxSocial conditionsy15th century. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aDowries.  aMarriage.  aMigration.  aValencia.  alower status women.  amedieval law.1 aWessell Lightfoot, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611245340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526112453423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526112453/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles